The '''Zeriuani''' or '''Zeruiani''' was a Slavic tribe mentioned by the 9th-century [[Bavarian Geographer]] ({{abbreviation|BG|Bavarian Geographer}}). It states that the Zeruiani "which is so great a realm that from it, as their tradition relates, all the tribes of the Slavs are sprung and trace their origin". Scholarship connect it to [[Procopius]]' ''[[Sporoi]]'', the [[Serbs]], and [[Severians]].
__NOTOC__
==Quote==
{{cquote|Zeruiani tantum est reguum, ut ex eo cunctae gentes Sclavorum exortae sint, et originem, sicut affirmant, ducant{{sfn|Šafařík|1865|p=29}}<br>''Zeruiani which is so great a realm that from it, as their tradition relates, all the tribes of the Slavs are sprung and trace their origin''{{sfn|Cross|1963|p=6}}}}

==Studies==
While earlier assumed by scholars to have been connected to early [[Serbs]] (or [[White Serbs]]), modern Polish scholars{{who|date=December 2017}} believe it is a corrupted form of the name of the [[Severians]]. It is claimed that the Serb ethnonym was never written with the Slavic suffix ''-jane'' (''-eani''), while the tribal name of the Severians was written in both collective ''Sever'' and plural ''Severjane'' form, etymologically implying Severian tribes. [[Gerard Labuda]] considered those tribes arrived from the [[Lesser Poland]] and western Ukraine, while Ryszard Kiersnowski assumed the Zeriuani were a relic of a large group which lived along the river [[Oder]], but as there was no recorded tribe with such a name in those parts it also indicates the Ruthenian and Balkan Severians.{{sfn|Witczak|2013|p=?}}

*According to German historian [[Johann Caspar Zeuss]] (1806–1856) they inhabited the Enns-Rhein line and were the earliest Serb tribe.{{sfn|Zeuss|1837|p=615}}

*According to Polish historian [[Joachim Lelewel]] (1786–1861), the Zeriuani referred to the "Serbs on the Dniester", while Zuireani (another tribe mentioned by BG) referred to the "[[Serbs]] in the Balkans".{{sfn|Persowski|1962|p=73}}{{sfn|Lelewel|1852|p=43}}{{quote needed|date=December 2017}}

*According to Slovak historian and ethnographer [[Pavel Jozef Šafárik]] (1795–1861), the Zeruiani were the [[White Serbs]] mentioned in ''[[De Administrando Imperio]]''.{{sfn|Šafařík|1865|p=29}}{{sfn|Persowski|1962|p=?}}

*According to Czech historian [[František Palacký]] (1798–1876), the Zeruiani were the Serbs.{{sfn|Palacký|1876|p=89}}

*According to Czech anthropologist [[Lubor Niederle]] (1865–1944), the name Zeruiani is a corruption of either Sarmatians, Serbs or Severians.<ref name="Niederle1923">{{cite book|author=Lubor Niederle|title=Manuel de l'antiquité slave ...|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SjANAAAAIAAJ|year=1923|publisher=É. Champion|p=19|quote=<!--confirmée par le titre même) un peuple nommé « Zeruiani, quod tantum est regnum ut ex eo cunctae gentes Sclauorum exortae sint et originen sicut affirmant durant » 1. Nous ne savons pas au juste, il est vrai, quel peuple l 'Anonyme bavarois entendait désigner par Zeruiani, ni si ce nom est une corruption de Sarmates ou de Serbes, ou du nom des Sêvériens de la Russie postérieure, mais, en tout cas, il s'agit d'un peuple qui se trouvait au nord du Danube et des Carpathes, quelque ...-->}}</ref>

*According to American Slavicist Samuel Hazzard Cross, the ethnonym Zeruiani was obviously related to the modern terms ''Serb'' and ''Sorb''.{{sfn|Cross|1963|p=6}}

*Some Serbian historians view the tribe as the [[Sporoi]] (a Greek rendering of ''*Sorpoi/Sorboi'') mentioned by Procopius, being the earliest Slavic tribe, that of Serbs.<ref>{{cite book|title=Serbian Studies|volume=2|issue=1–4|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fOcVAQAAMAAJ|year=1982|publisher=North American Society for Serbian Studies|p=21}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Александар М Петровић|title=Праисторија Срба: разматрање грађе за стару повесницу|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cV4MAQAAMAAJ|year=2004|publisher=Пешић и синови|p=307}}</ref>

